The health sector can probably be pardoned for not seeing the pandemic coming. But still, this is no excuse for the ministry’s lack of preparation to have enough equipment such as ventilators and hospital beds to avert unforeseen emergencies. 
On the other hand, the Ministry of Education should have prepared schools with more infrastructure and resources. Public schools still struggle with poor facilities like classrooms and toilets. Now, with the pandemic still surging, our lack of preparation may be to our country’s detriment.





Since schools were closed early last year, the Ministry of Education should have put proper measures in place in readiness for reopening. The government had stated that schools would reopen on January 4, but it is appalling to witness the last-minute preparations. 
Preparedness requires collaborative efforts from all stakeholders. It also calls for proper planning and resources allocation to achieve effortless results. The ministries of health and education should ensure that as children resume learning, none will be put at risk of contracting the virus. 
Early preparations
This is not to belittle the efforts done by both ministries so far. If anything, they ought to be applauded for their efforts. However, a lot more could still have been done.



